          <div class=3D"note" role=3D"note" id=3D"issue-container-generated=
ID-26"><div role=3D"heading" class=3D"note-title marker" id=3D"h-note-26" a=
ria-level=3D"5"><span>Note</span></div><p class=3D"">
            Going forward, this algorithm is intended to be externally call=
ed and run in any case
            where the attached <a data-link-type=3D"idl" data-lt=3D"MediaSo=
urce" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/media-source/#dom-mediasource" class=3D=
"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediasource-85"><code>MediaSource</code></a=
>, if any, must be detached from the media element. It
            <em class=3D"rfc2119">MAY</em> be called on HTMLMediaElement [<=
cite><a class=3D"bibref" data-link-type=3D"biblio" href=3D"https://w3c.gith=
ub.io/media-source/#bib-html" title=3D"HTML Standard">HTML</a></cite>] oper=
ations like load() and <a data-link-type=3D"dfn" href=3D"https://html.spec.=
whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#concept-media-load-resource">resource fetch=
 algorithm</a> failures in addition to, or in place of, when the media elem=
ent transitions
            to <a data-link-type=3D"const" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg=
.org/multipage/media.html#dom-media-network_empty"><code>NETWORK_EMPTY</cod=
e></a>. Resource fetch algorithm failures are those
            which abort either the resource fetch algorithm or the resource=
 selection algorithm,
            with the exception that the "Final step" [<cite><a class=3D"bib=
ref" data-link-type=3D"biblio" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/media-source/#=
bib-html" title=3D"HTML Standard">HTML</a></cite>] is not considered a fail=
ure that
            triggers detachment.
