-conformance"><bdi class=3D"secno">15. </bdi>Conformance</h2><a class=3D"se=
lf-link" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/media-source/#conformance" aria-labe=
l=3D"Permalink for Section 15."></a></div><p>As well as sections marked as =
non-normative, all authoring guidelines, diagrams, examples, and notes in t=
his specification are non-normative. Everything else in this specification =
is normative.</p><p>
        The key words <em class=3D"rfc2119">MAY</em>, <em class=3D"rfc2119"=
>MUST</em>, <em class=3D"rfc2119">MUST NOT</em>, <em class=3D"rfc2119">SHOU=
LD</em>, and <em class=3D"rfc2119">SHOULD NOT</em> in this document
        are to be interpreted as described in
        <a href=3D"https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/bcp14">BCP 14</a>
        [<cite><a class=3D"bibref" data-link-type=3D"biblio" href=3D"https:=
//w3c.github.io/media-source/#bib-rfc2119" title=3D"Key words for use in RF=
Cs to Indicate Requirement Levels">RFC2119</a></cite>] [<cite><a class=3D"b=
ibref" data-link-type=3D"biblio" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/media-source=
/#bib-rfc8174" title=3D"Ambiguity of Uppercase vs Lowercase in RFC 2119 Key=
 Words">RFC8174</a></cite>]
        when, and only when, they appear in all
        capitals, as shown here.
      </p></section>
